00:00:04.356 --> 00:00:05.860
- Good morning, everyone.

00:00:05.860 --> 00:00:07.700
It's wonderful to see you.

00:00:07.700 --> 00:00:10.610
I am Tomiko Brown-Nagin, the
dean of the Radcliffe Institute

00:00:10.610 --> 00:00:13.460
for Advanced Study here
at Harvard University.

00:00:13.460 --> 00:00:17.870
Welcome to our annual gender
conference, focused this year

00:00:17.870 --> 00:00:21.170
on the intersection of
gender and communication

00:00:21.170 --> 00:00:23.780
beyond spoken words.

00:00:23.780 --> 00:00:26.510
Last night, we kicked
off our conference

00:00:26.510 --> 00:00:29.120
with an exploration
of communication

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:31.430
through the lens
of drag culture.

00:00:31.430 --> 00:00:34.370
It was quite a great evening.

00:00:34.370 --> 00:00:36.320
If you couldn't
join us, I encourage

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:39.790
you to watch the recording
of that evening that'll

00:00:39.790 --> 00:00:42.350
be posted online.

00:00:42.350 --> 00:00:46.280
Today, we consider the
aesthetics of communication

00:00:46.280 --> 00:00:50.750
through topics as diverse
as tattoos, perfume,

00:00:50.750 --> 00:00:55.970
animal behavior, robots,
sign language, and dance.

00:00:55.970 --> 00:00:58.790
The program will engage
our minds and senses.

00:00:58.790 --> 00:01:01.370
And I expect it'll
reveal aspects

00:01:01.370 --> 00:01:03.980
of unspoken communication
that many of us

00:01:03.980 --> 00:01:07.250
might not have
considered before.

00:01:07.250 --> 00:01:09.920
Interdisciplinarity
is the very core

00:01:09.920 --> 00:01:14.360
of what we do here at Radcliffe,
and it permeates every session

00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:16.550
of this convening.

00:01:16.550 --> 00:01:18.680
As we engage today,
I hope you'll

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:21.320
keep in mind yesterday
evening's discussion

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:25.970
and consider how the examples of
bodily communication we explore

00:01:25.970 --> 00:01:30.160
relate to issues of
equity, opportunity,

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:33.950
and inclusion, another
core element of Radcliffe's

00:01:33.950 --> 00:01:35.570
identity.

00:01:35.570 --> 00:01:40.250
It's still a reality that
many individuals are demeaned,

00:01:40.250 --> 00:01:43.490
devalued, and discriminated
against because of how they

00:01:43.490 --> 00:01:46.100
express their gender
identity and how

00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:51.200
others perceive it are for
pushing against gender norms.

00:01:51.200 --> 00:01:55.790
This past fall, a public
library system in Louisiana

00:01:55.790 --> 00:01:58.790
prohibited a story
hour event because it

00:01:58.790 --> 00:02:03.290
would feature drag queens
reading children's books.

00:02:03.290 --> 00:02:06.810
Similar reading programs
exist across the country,

00:02:06.810 --> 00:02:10.160
including here in the
Cambridge-Boston area.

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:14.900
And so, too, do efforts
to censor drag performers,

00:02:14.900 --> 00:02:20.000
whether in libraries,
onstage, or elsewhere.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:22.790
In our nation's schools,
students are frequently

00:02:22.790 --> 00:02:25.070
disciplined because
their appearance

00:02:25.070 --> 00:02:31.220
violates dress codes that hinge
on traditional gender norms.

00:02:31.220 --> 00:02:33.920
And research shows
that these dress codes

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:38.330
are disproportionately enforced
against black girls, who

00:02:38.330 --> 00:02:42.050
tend to be perceived by
adults as less innocent, more

00:02:42.050 --> 00:02:47.810
adult-like, and more sexual as
compared to their white peers.

00:02:47.810 --> 00:02:50.120
Transgender and
gender-nonconforming

00:02:50.120 --> 00:02:53.810
individuals experience
mistreatment, discrimination,

00:02:53.810 --> 00:02:58.160
and even violence at
particularly alarming rates.

00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:02.030
A staggering 83% of
transgender youth

00:03:02.030 --> 00:03:07.250
and 69% of gender-nonconforming
youth in grades 6 through 12

00:03:07.250 --> 00:03:11.300
report being bullied
or harassed at school.

00:03:11.300 --> 00:03:14.270
I mention these examples because
they illustrate the importance

00:03:14.270 --> 00:03:17.630
of thinking intersectionally.

00:03:17.630 --> 00:03:20.720
Bodily communication
and how others perceive

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:23.810
that communication varies
in meaningful ways,

00:03:23.810 --> 00:03:26.720
not only across
gender but also as

00:03:26.720 --> 00:03:31.100
to race, sexual orientation,
class, ability, nationality,

00:03:31.100 --> 00:03:32.690
and so much more.

00:03:32.690 --> 00:03:34.940
This is something to keep
in the back of our minds

00:03:34.940 --> 00:03:38.030
today as we dive into
this illuminating

00:03:38.030 --> 00:03:42.440
conversation focused on the
aesthetics of communication.

